This paper is likely to belong to the category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) as it proposes a new transition-based parser for AMR parsing. It also involves the use of machine learning techniques to improve the alignment and parsing process, which falls under the categories of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper involves the use of optimization techniques to improve the performance of the parser, which falls under the category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper involves the use of natural language processing techniques to parse sentences into AMR graphs, which falls under the category of Information Retrieval (cs.IR).
